2. WHO EPIDEMIOLOGICAL BULLETIN SUMMARY FOR PERIOD 17 to 21 June 1996 (taken
from WHO Automatic Fax Reply Service +41 22 791 41 98)
CHOLERA
Malaysia: The outbreak of cholera which began in Penang on 10 May has been
contained and no new cases have been reported since 31 May. Some cases were
reported in Kedah State until 6 June. No deaths have occurred during this
outbreak. All preventive and control measures are being carried out in
accordance with WHO guidelines.
Malaysia - Penang (Island) State has been removed from the infected area list.
Autonomous Republic of Dagestan (Russian Federation) has been removed from the
infected area list.

LASSA FEVER
Sierra Leone: In collaboration with the Ministry of Health and Sanitation and
the Lassa Fever Research Project, the WHO support team, with a specialist from
CDC, Atlanta, has assessed the extent and severity of the outbreak after making
field trips to Kailahun and Kenema Districts. Drugs and supplies and
specialized nursing support have been provided as well as the organization of a
workshop for health personnel. A total of 167 cases and 60 deaths were recorded
during the period 1 January to 28 May 1996.

DENGUE/DENGUE HAEMORRHAGIC FEVER
Indonesia: Over the last 5 months 12 093 cases and 260 deaths have occurred in
23 of the 27 provinces of Indonesia. The highest number of cases occurred in
East Java (3346 cases, 62 deaths). Dengue usually occurs in densely populated
areas and a campaign to educate the public on keeping the environment clean and
free of stagnant water, the breeding place for mosqitos, has been stepped up.


*********************************************************************
3. Item(s) published on WHO World Wide Web EMC Outbreak Information pages
(http://www.who.ch/programmes/emc/news.htm) this week (date of posting
indicated)
14 June (ii):
DENGUE/DENGUE HAEMORRHAGIC FEVER:
Malaysia: The dengue season has started in Malaysia with 2450 cases
reported throughout the country by 1 June 1996 according to information
from the WHO Collaborating Centre for Dengue/Dengue Haemorrhagic Fever in
Kuala Lumpur. The States most affected are the Federal Territory,
Selangor, Perak, Johor and Pahang. The present season is expected to
continue for the next few months reaching a peak in July/August. Active
vector control measures are in place in all states.
Indonesia: Over the last five months there have been over 5000 cases of
dengue/dengue haemorrhagic fever and 117 deaths in 11 of the 27 provinces
of Indonesia.
The highest number of cases occurred in East Java. Dengue usually occurs
in densely populated areas and a campaign to educate the public on keeping
the environment clean and free of stagnant water, the breeding place for
mosquitoes, has been stepped up.
Background information on Dengue Haemorrhagic Fever can be found in WHO
Fact Sheet No. 117
